Chop the @baking potato{1} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel!). Trim the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways then thinly slice widthways. Trim the @carrot{2}, halve lengthways then thinly slice widthways. Trim, then thinly slice the @spring onion{1}. Grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Put the @lamb mince{200%g} in a #mixing bowl{} with the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g}, half the @dried thyme{1/4%tsp} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{pinch}. Mix together with your hands and make four small meatballs per person. Heat a drizzle of @oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. Once hot, add the meatballs and @British smoked bacon lardons{60%g}. Brown them both, turning often, for ~{5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

Meanwhile, bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{400%ml} with a @salt{pinch} to the boil.

Place the potato in the pan of boiling water and cook until tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> TIP: The potato is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Meanwhile, once browned, remove the meatballs and pancetta from the frying pan to a #plate{}. Return the pan to medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{1%tsp} (if needed). Fill and boil your #kettle{}.

Add the leek, carrot and remaining @dried thyme{1/4%tsp} to the frying pan. Cook until beginning to soften, ~{5%minutes}. Meanwhile, pour the boiling water into a #measuring jug{}. Add the @red wine stock paste{28%g} and stir to dissolve. Stir the garlic and @plain flour{8%g} into the veggies and cook for ~{1%minute}. Next, pour in the stock and return the meatballs and pancetta to the pan.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until the veggies are tender and the lamb cooked through, ~{15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The meatballs are cooked when they are no longer pink in the middle.

Once the potato is cooked, drain in a #colander{} then return to the pan (off the heat). Mash with @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{pinch} (and a knob of @?butter{knob} if you have some!). Stir in the spring onion.

When the stew is ready, remove from the heat and season to taste with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed. Serve the spring onion mash in #bowls{} topped with the Irish stew. Happy St Patrick's Day!